艾可格斯費爾德","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"英國英格蘭艾可格斯費爾德","lifeSummary":"當Mary Ellen Smith於1361年出生在英國英格蘭艾可格斯費爾德時，她的父親Smith27歲，母親Smith25歲。她於1390年與Sir Henry Hunte在英國艾可格斯費爾德結婚。他們至少是2個兒子的父母。她去世於1420年在她的家鄉享年59歲。"},"zh-hans":{"1361–1420":"1361年–1420年","1355–1437":"1355年–1437年","1380–1452":"1380年–1452年","1387–Male":"1387年–殁","1335–Male":"1335年–殁","1337–Female":"1337年–殁","1437":"1437年","1337":"1337年","1335":"1335年","1355":"1355年","1387":"1387年","1420":"1420年","1452":"1452年","1361":"1361年","1380":"1380年","1390":"1390年","Gosfield, Essex, England":"英国艾可格斯費爾德","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"英国英格兰艾可格斯費爾德","lifeSummary":"当Mary Ellen Smith于1361年出生在英国英格兰艾可格斯費爾德时，她的父亲Smith27岁，母亲Smith25岁。她于1390年与Sir Henry Hunte在英国艾可格斯費爾德结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。她去世于1420年在她的家乡享年59岁。"},"hr":{"1361–1420":"1361.–1420.","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380.–1452","1387–Male":"1387.–preminuo","1335–Male":"1335–preminuo","1337–Female":"1337–preminula","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387.","1420":"1420.","1452":"1452","1361":"1361.","1380":"1380.","1390":"1390.","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1361–1420":"1361–1420","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380–1452","1387–Male":"1387–Zesnulý","1335–Male":"1335–Zesnulý","1337–Female":"1337–Zesnulá","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, Anglie","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1361–1420":"1361–1420","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380–1452","1387–Male":"1387–Afdød","1335–Male":"1335–Afdød","1337–Female":"1337–Afdød","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1361–1420":"1361–1420","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380–1452","1387–Male":"1387–Overleden","1335–Male":"1335–Overleden","1337–Female":"1337–Overleden","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1361–1420":"1361–1420","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380–1452","1387–Male":"1387–Deceased","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1337–Female":"1337–Deceased","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smithe","meanings":["(1997: 115;2007: 306; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smither","meanings":["English (Surrey): occupational name from Middle English <i>smith(i)ere</i>, <i>smeth(i)ere</i> ‘blacksmith’, a derivative of Middle English <i>smithen</i>, <i>smethen</i>, ‘to make (something) in metal, to forge’. Compare   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smithey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from Middle English <i>smithi</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old Norse <i>smithja</i>), used either as a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, or an occupational name for someone who worked in one. Compare   Smith   and   Smead  ."]},{"name":"Smyth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."]},{"name":"Smythe","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"McGowan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Siobhan, Cormac, Seamus, Aileen, Colm, Eithne, Kieran, Niall, Paddy.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (a') Ghobhainn</b> or <b>Mac Gobhann</b> (Scottish) or <b>Mac (an) Ghabhann</b> (Irish), ‘son of (the) smith’. This name has also been Anglicized as   Smith   and   Smithson  ."]},{"name":"Smead","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>smeth(e)</i> ‘smith’, a phonetic variant of   Smith   1 that was widespread in medieval England, especially in south-eastern and south-western counties.","topographic, occupational, and habitational name from Middle English <i>smethe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smethe</i>), a side form of   Smith   2, for someone who lived and worked at a blacksmith's, or who lived in or came from a place so named, such as Smeeth (Kent) or Smeed Farm in Hastingleigh (Kent). Compare the synonymous   Smithey  ."]},{"name":"Faber","meanings":["German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Danish; Slovak and Czech (mainly <b>Fáber</b>): occupational name from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘blacksmith’. At the time of the Reformation, it was much used as a humanistic name, a translation into Latin of vernacular surnames such as German   Schmidt   and Dutch   Smit  . Compare   Fabri   and   Fauber  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also part of a title. It was François Lefebvre, <i>sieur</i> Duplessis Faber from Paris, France, whose title <i>sieur Duplessis Faber</i> was shortened into the surname <i>Faber</i>. He married Marie-Madeleine Chorel in Champlain, QC, in 1689."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Hebrew.  See  <b>Maria</b>   and   <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Ellen Smith was born in 1361, in Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Smith, was 27 and her mother, Smith, was 25. She married Sir Henry Hunte in 1390, in Gosfield, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1420, in her hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1361–1420":"1361–1420","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380–1452","1387–Male":"1387–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1361–1420":"1361–1420","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380–1452","1387–Male":"1387–Kuollut","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1337–Female":"1337–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1361–1420":"1361–1420","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1380–1452":"1380–1452","1387–Male":"1387–Décédé","1335–Male":"1335–Décédé","1337–Female":"1337–Décédée","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Gosfield, Essex, Eng